  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime. It is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal or legitimate (making it look \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: **placement, layering, and integration**. Money laundering is a serious offense because it allows criminals to profit from their illegal activities, undermines the integrity of financial systems, and can fund further criminal enterprises.\n\nMost countries have strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and financial institutions are required to report suspicious activities to authorities. Penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. International organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), also work to set global standards and promote effective implementation of measures to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.",
